label.value: positive regulation of unidimensional cell growth

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of unidimensional cell growth, the process in which a cell irreversibly increases in size in one [spatial] dimension or along one axis.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of monopolar cell growth, polarized growth from one end of a cell.

label.value: negative regulation of monopolar cell growth

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of monopolar cell growth, polarized growth from one end of a cell.

label.value: positive regulation of monopolar cell growth

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of monopolar cell growth, polarized growth from one end of a cell.
Any process that initiates the inactive process of monopolar cell growth, polarized growth from one end of a cell.

label.value: cell growth mode switching, monopolar to bipolar

value.value: The process in which a cell switches from monopolar cell growth to bipolar cell growth.
Binding to an iron-sulfur cluster, a combination of iron and sulfur atoms.
Binding to a cluster of atoms including both metal ions and nonmetal atoms, usually sulfur and oxygen. Examples include iron-sulfur clusters and nickel-iron-sulfur clusters.
The modification of histone H3 by addition of one or more methyl groups to lysine at position 9 of the histone.
The modification of histone H3 by addition of one or more methyl groups to lysine at position 4 of the histone.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent addition of a methyl group to the lysine at position 4 of histone H3.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent addition of a methyl group to the lysine at position 9 of histone H3.

label.value: positive regulation of histone H3-K4 methylation

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent addition of a methyl group to the lysine at position 4 of histone H3.

label.value: negative regulation of histone H3-K4 methylation

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent addition of a methyl group to the lysine at position 4 of histone H3.

label.value: negative regulation of histone H3-K9 methylation

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent addition of a methyl group to the lysine at position 9 of histone H3.

label.value: positive regulation of histone H3-K9 methylation

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the covalent addition of a methyl group to the lysine at position 9 of histone H3.

Catalysis of the beta-elimination of the 5' deoxyribose-5-phosphate at an abasic site in DNA where a DNA-(apurinic or apyrimidinic site) lyase has already cleaved the C-O-P bond 3' to the apurinic or apyrimidinic site.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cAMP (cyclic AMP, adenosine 3',5'-cyclophosphate) stimulus.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a calcium ion stimulus.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a methylglyoxal stimulus. Methylglyoxal is a 2-oxoaldehyde derived from propanal.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of methylglyoxal, CH3-CO-CHO, the aldehyde of pyruvic acid.

label.value: proteolysis involved in protein catabolic process

value.value: The hydrolysis of a peptide bond or bonds within a protein as part of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein by individual cells.
Any process leading to the attainment of the full functional capacity of a protein.
The series of events in which a stimulus is received by a cell or organism and converted into a molecular signal.
Any process in which an organelle is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location.

A cellular localization process whereby a substance or cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within a cell including the localization of substances or cellular entities to the cell membrane.
Any process in which endoplasmic reticulum is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within the cell.
Any process in which a mitochondrion or mitochondria are transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within the cell.
Any process in which the nucleus is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within the cell.
Any process, occuring in a cell, that localizes a substance or cellular component. This may occur via movement, tethering or selective degradation.

Any process in which a substance or cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, is maintained in a specific location within, or in the membrane of, a cell, and is prevented from moving elsewhere.
Any process in which is the spindle is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location.
The directed movement of an organelle to a specific location.
Any process in which nuclear pores are transported to, or maintained in, a specific location.

Any process in which membrane rafts are transported to, or maintained in, a specific location. Membrane rafts are small (10-200 nm), heterogeneous, highly dynamic, sterol- and sphingolipid-enriched membrane domains that compartmentalize cellular processes.

Any process in which actin cortical patches are transported to, or maintained in, a specific location. An actin cortical patch is a discrete actin-containing structure found just beneath the plasma membrane in fungal cells.
Any process in which a substance or cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within a membrane.

label.value: biological process involved in intraspecies interaction between organisms

value.value: Any process in which an organism has an effect on an organism of the same species.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus. The process begins with detection of the stimulus by a cell and ends with a change in state or activity or the cell.

definition.value: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

value.value: Any process that modulates the rate or extent of progression through the cell cycle.
The cell cycle process in which centromeres of sister chromatids are joined during meiosis.
The cell cycle process in which sister chromatid arms are physically detached from each other during meiosis.
The process in which sister chromatids are physically detached from each other during meiosis.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell division.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cell division.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of nuclear division, the partitioning of the nucleus and its genetic information.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of nuclear division, the partitioning of the nucleus and its genetic information.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of nuclear division, the partitioning of the nucleus and its genetic information.

Binding to G-quadruplex DNA structures, in which groups of four guanines adopt a flat, cyclic Hoogsteen hydrogen-bonding arrangement known as a guanine tetrad. The stacking of guanine tetrads results in G-quadruplex DNA structures. G-quadruplex DNA can form under physiological conditions from some G-rich sequences, such as those found in telomeres, immunoglobulin switch regions, gene promoters, fragile X repeats, and the dimerization domain in the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) genome.
Catalysis of the reaction: [protein]-dithol + ROOH = [protein]-disulfide + H2O + ROH.

definition.value: Includes redox chemistry as part of the catalytic reaction (2 R'-SH = R'-S-S-R'), where R' refers to peroxiredoxin itself). Not to be confused with GO:0004601 (peroxidase activity, EC:1.11.1.7), which has a different reaction mechanism.
